# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angelika-mertens
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 16 October 1994 to elect the members of the 13th Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU alliance led by Helmut Kohl remained the largest faction in parliament, with Kohl remaining Chancellor in a narrowly re-elected coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] This elected Bundestag was the largest in history until 2017, numbering 672 members.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Even though this election did not lead to a switch in government, it saw the election of many people to the Bundestag who would play an important role later.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Future CDU leaders Friedrich Merz and Armin Laschet were first elected to the Bundestag in 1994, as were future cabinet ministers Norbert Röttgen and Peter Altmaier.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] This was the last election until 2009 that a centre-right government was elected.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) let its members elect a candidate for chancellor against Helmut Kohl after SPD leader Björn Engholm and chancellor candidate-designate had to resign in 1993 amid scandal.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Rudolf Scharping, Minister-President of Rhineland-Palatinate, beat Gerhard Schröder and Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul in the SPD's internal election.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Scharping was only elected with 40 percent of the vote and relied on campaigning with other SPD leaders and rivals such as Oskar Lafontaine and Gerhard Schröder, both self-confident and outspoken, in a "troika".
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Tension between them greatly hurt his campaign.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] In addition, Scharping was seen as a weak leader due to his lack of charisma and media skills, and therefore did not induce a lot of enthusiasm.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] For the first time in their existence, Alliance 90/The Greens seemed to be willing to join a government in case a centre-left SPD–Greens coalition had a workable majority in the Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The election also saw a "red socks" campaign used by the centre-right, including the CDU/CSU and the Free Democratic Party (FDP), to scare off a possible red–red–green coalition (SPD–Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS)–Greens).
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Analysts have stated that such a strategy likely paid off, as it was seen as one of the decisive elements for the narrow victory of Kohl for the CDU/CSU–FDP.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The campaign was criticized as an obvious attempt to discredit the whole political left; the PDS reinterpreted it for itself by printing red socks.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP was able to continue in power with Helmut Kohl as chancellor.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] The PDS won four constituency seats in its power base of the former East Berlin, qualifying it for proportional representation even though the party won 4.4 percent of the vote, just short of the 5% electoral threshold required for full parliamentary status.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit regional parties, any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:angelika-mertens/1994-german-federal-election] This was the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that the FDP was not the third-largest party in the chamber.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 18 September 2005 to elect the members of the 16th Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The snap election was called after the government's defeat in the North Rhine-Westphalia state election, which caused them to intentionally lose a motion of confidence to trigger an early federal election.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The outgoing government was a coalition of the centre-left Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and Alliance 90/The Greens, led by federal chancellor Gerhard Schröder.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The election was originally intended for the autumn of 2006.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The opposition Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU), with its sister party the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU), started the campaign with a strong lead over the SPD in opinion polls.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The government was generally expected to suffer a major defeat and be replaced by a coalition of the CDU/CSU and the liberal Free Democratic Party (FDP), with CDU leader Angela Merkel becoming chancellor.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] However, the CDU/CSU ultimately lost vote share compared to its 2002 result, falling to 35%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The SPD suffered losses but finished just one percentage point behind the CDU/CSU, winning 34%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Exit polls showed clearly that neither the SPD–Green nor CDU/CSU–FDP coalitions had won a majority of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The FDP placed third on just under 10% of votes, its best result since 1990, while the Greens suffered small losses.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The major stumbling block to a parliamentary majority was the new Left Party, led by Gregor Gysi and former SPD chairman Oskar Lafontaine, which won 8.7% of votes and 54 seats.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and SPD both rejected cooperation with the Left Party.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Both Schröder and Merkel claimed victory, but the formation of a new government required careful negotiations, as no conventional arrangement could achieve a majority.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU sought talks with the Greens, but were unable to find common ground.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Discussions ultimately began for a grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] On 10 October, officials from both parties indicated that negotiations had concluded successfully and that they would form a coalition government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The Bundestag met on 22 November and Merkel was elected chancellor, with 397 votes in favour.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] On 22 May 2005, state elections were held in North Rhine-Westphalia, the most populous state of Germany, where the SPD had led the state government continuously since 1966.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The election saw the government of Minister-President Peer Steinbrück defeated.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] It also resulted in the opposition CDU and FDP claiming a majority in the Bundesrat, the upper house of the federal legislature.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The same day, federal Chancellor Schröder and SPD Bundestag group leader Franz Müntefering announced they would seek early federal elections.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] They claimed the North Rhine-Westphalia result was indicative of a lack of public confidence in the federal government.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Early federal elections may only be held under two circumstances: if the Bundestag rejects a candidate for chancellor three times, or if a motion of confidence in the government fails to achieve an absolute majority in the Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In either case, the president may, at request of the chancellor, dissolve the Bundestag and order new elections.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The latter method had been utilised on two occasions previously, in 1972 and 1983, by incumbent governments intentionally failing motions of confidence.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Schröder became the third chancellor to do this, with a motion of confidence on 1 July failing with 151 votes in favour, 296 against, and 148 abstentions.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Schröder called on SPD members to abstain from the vote, which would allow him to fall short of the required threshold.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] President Horst Köhler then dissolved the Bundestag and scheduled new elections.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU nominated Angela Merkel for chancellor, the first time in German history that one of the two larger parties had nominated a woman for this position.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU presented a platform involving increasing the pace and scope of economic deregulation in Germany and pursuing cuts in income tax and public spending (many commentators have compared Merkel with Margaret Thatcher).
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU began the campaign with a 21% lead over the SPD and confidence in Merkel's victory led the prime minister of the United Kingdom, Tony Blair, to meet with her ahead of Chancellor Schröder during a visit to Berlin in June.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The SPD had the goal of maintaining the current deregulation agenda.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The Greens decided on their program in July 2005.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Compared to their previous federal election program, they increased the emphasis on economics and labour-market politics.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] For the first time this topic came before the classical green topic of environmental politics in the program.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In general, the program moved slightly to the left; including stating the necessity for changes to some existing red-green governmental policies.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The FDP announced its election program before any other party, publishing it on 24 July.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] It called for strong saving measures in public spending and more room for local negotiation between employees and employers, as opposed to central control by trade-union officials.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The leaders of the left wing Party of Democratic Socialism (the "PDS") agreed to let candidates of the recently founded Electoral Alternative for Labor and Social Justice (the "WASG") run on their party list, leaving open the possible future option of a merger between the two parties.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In agreeing to this the WASG stipulated that the PDS rename itself as the Left Party.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The WASG, with its front-runner Oskar Lafontaine (a former SPD leader), formed from breakaway elements within the SPD, angered at that party taking a "neoliberal" direction in economic reforms.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The general membership had already approved this measure and awaited to hear from the PDS party convention to agree as well.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Since German electoral law does not permit common lists of two or more parties, in practice the DVU did not enter the election, and members of that party appeared on the NPD list.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Early election polls during summer 2005 from 6 organizations showed a solid lead for the CDU/CSU with a share of the vote ranging between 41% and 43%, and the SPD trailing at between 32% and 34%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The polls further showed the FDP, a possible coalition partner for the conservatives, at between 6.5% and 8%, and the Greens, the current coalition partner for the SPD, between 6% and 8%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Most polls indicated a likely majority for a CDU/CSU-FDP coalition.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] As for other parties, those polls which explicitly included the PDS-WASG electoral alliance showed it above the 5% hurdle at between 7% and 8.5%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] No poll showed any other parties, including far-right parties, near 5%, although far-right parties had in the past sometimes polled below their actual support due to unwillingness by voters to admit their support.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In early August, support for Angela Merkel declined considerably.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Reasons for this included conflicts about the election program in and between the conservative parties (the CDU and the CSU), and arguments with their preferred coalition partner, the FDP, as well as embarrassing gaffes.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] At one point the media criticized Merkel for confusing net and gross income figures during a campaign speech.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Following this, polls suggested that the CDU/CSU and FDP would only win 48% of votes between them, and thus would not be able to form a government.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Further damage occurred when two prominent CDU/CSU candidates, Jörg Schönbohm and the CSU leader Edmund Stoiber, made insulting remarks about East Germans.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] These remarks not only alienated voters in Eastern Germany but also made some question the CDU/CSU's confidence in Merkel, as she herself grew up in the East.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] However, polls carried out by the *Süddeutsche Zeitung* in late August showed the CDU/CSU/FDP bloc back up at 51% of the vote.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Predictions suggested that the opposing bloc of incumbent Chancellor Gerhard Schröder's ruling Social Democrats, the Greens and the country's recently formed left-wing Left Party (PDS/WASG alliance) would win a combined total of only 46%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The leaders of the SPD and the Greens, Schröder and Fischer, as well as the Left Party's front-runner Gregor Gysi said they opposed the idea of a "red-red-green" coalition.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] With polls remaining so close, speculation increased that (as in the elections of 1994, 1998 and 2002) a small number of overhang seats might significantly impact the election results.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] On Sunday 4 September, Schröder and Merkel met in a head-to-head debate which was broadcast by four of Germany's major private and public television networks.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Although most commentators gave the initial edge to Merkel, polls soon showed that the general public disagreed and ranked Schröder the clear winner.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Later analysis suggested that Merkel's support for a flat-tax proposal by Paul Kirchhof, the shadow Finance Minister, further undermined her credibility on economic affairs and gave the impression that the CDU's economic reforms would only benefit the very rich.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Midweek polls showed the SPD clawing their way upwards by a few percentage points although the combined CDU/CSU and FDP votes tended to remain 1 to 2 percentage points ahead of those for the left-wing parties combined.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] On the eve of the election, the CDU enjoyed a 9% lead over the SPD (42% and 33% respectively), albeit with neither party likely to have enough seats (even with their preferred coalition partners) to form a government.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Merkel's personal popularity (consistently below that of her party) had climbed back up to 40%, from a low of 30% while Schröder's had reached a peak of 53% (consistently exceeding that of his party).
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] However, polls also showed that even at this late stage, a quarter of German voters had not yet decided how to vote and that these undecided voters could decide the final result if they turned out to vote.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] With polls still so close, the parties broke with tradition and continued campaigning on the Saturday before the election and on election day itself.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] While pundits focused on the likelihood of a grand coalition, the CDU suggested that the SPD might consent to forming a coalition with the new Left Party.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] All major opinion polling published in the week prior to the election indicated a clear victory for the CDU/CSU, with a result over 40%.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The discrepancy between forecasts and the actual result led to criticism of the polling firms.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The error was attributed to factors including the large number of undecided voters (up to 40% ahead of the election) and the increasing inaccuracy of traditional telephone-based survey methods.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Germany went to the polls on 18 September 2005.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Voters in one constituency in Dresden had to wait until 2 October to vote in order to allow the reprinting of ballot-papers after the death of the National Democratic Party candidate on 8 September.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Soon after voting ended, it became clear that the CDU/CSU (the "Union") had narrowly edged out the SPD.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] However, neither of the two likely coalitions (SPD-Greens and CDU/CSU-FDP) could achieve a *Kanzlermehrheit* – the support of the majority of members of the Bundestag required to elect a chancellor.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] This meant that Germany had a hung parliament as no coalition could hold an overall parliamentary majority.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Exit polls for both the ARD and the ZDF television networks showed the CDU/CSU on 35%, the SPD on 34%, the FDP on 10%, the Left Party on 9% and the Greens on 8%; a Forsa poll differed slightly, predicting 36% for the CDU/CSU and 8% for the Left Party.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Early seat projections suggested that the CDU/CSU and the SPD had virtually tied in the count for seats in the Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The exit polls and projections proved broadly accurate in the preliminary results released on 19 September and in the final results published on 7 October.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The SPD/Green coalition's number of seats fell from 306 seats (in a house of 603), to 273 seats (in a house of 614) while the opposition, the CDU/CSU-FDP coalition's number of seats fell from 295 seats to 286 seats.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Both potential coalitions fell far short of the 308 seats required for a majority in this Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The Left Party and the FDP overtook the Greens, previously Germany's third most-popular party since 1994.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The FDP, with almost 10% of the vote, scored its best result since the 1990 federal election, regaining its status as the Federal Republic's third party, which it had enjoyed throughout the history of West Germany and maintained in the first post-German reunification election.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Some analysts believe that the rise in the FDP vote came as a result of tactical voting by CDU-CSU voters hoping to prevent a grand coalition by buttressing the Free Democrats.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Of the parties that failed to secure the 5% needed to attain seats in the Bundestag, the National Democratic Party performed best, winning 1.6% of the list vote and 1.8% of the constituency vote.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The 2005 election was the last one until 2021 where the SPD won all single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland as well as Brandenburg and the last time where they won any single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Only in the 2021 election, at the end of the Merkel era, would the SPD sweep all constituencies in Saarland and Brandenburg again and gain seats in Saxony-Anhalt.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Both Angela Merkel (CDU) and Gerhard Schröder (SPD) claimed victory and the chancellorship as the exit polls came in.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] It soon became clear that neither could form a majority government within the existing coalitions.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Largely because of strong hostility between Schröder and Oskar Lafontaine, a former SPD chairman turned leader of the Left Party, the obvious left-wing coalition of the SPD, Greens and Left Party was not possible.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] However, both the CDU and SPD said that they would negotiate with all parties that had won seats except the Left Party, while the leaders of the Left Party rejected any possibility of participating in a coalition with either of the two main parties.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In the Elefantenrunde (elephant round) programme on election night featuring all party leaders, Schröder, in a memorable performance, insisted he had won on the basis of how far behind the SPD was in pre-election polls but managing to close the gap with the CDU/CSU to just one percent.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Although the SPD still fell behind the CDU/CSU, he said "nobody but me is capable of building a stable coalition" and accused the moderators of having "an intellectual problem".
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The chancellor then declared to Merkel "Under her leadership she will never get a coalition with my party" and insisted that the CDU and CSU should be treated as separate parties.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] His performance during the programme was criticized by the media, CDU/CSU and the FDP as "shocking", "egocentric", "arrogant" and "bizarre".
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The Berliner Kurier newspaper headline asked if Schröder was "intoxicated by his victory or did he have one glass of wine too many?".
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Schröder himself later called his behavior "suboptimal" but denied he was drunk.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Despite some prominent members publicly blaming Merkel for its poor showing, the CDU/CSU confirmed her as leader on 20 September.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] On 22 September, following Schröder's election night comments, SPD members began musing that the political system should consider the CDU and the CSU as separate entities rather than as a single parliamentary faction.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] In such a scenario, the SPD would be the largest party in the Bundestag and thus, they argued, an SPD member should become chancellor in any grand coalition.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] One SPD legislator indicated he planned to introduce a motion in the Bundestag explicitly defining the CDU and the CSU as separate parties.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The Greens rejected coalition with the CDU/CSU after talks broke down.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU pressed their case for the Chancellery after victory in the delayed vote in Dresden, and ahead of talks with the SPD; the SPD maintained their own claim, but Schröder indicated that he would step aside if his party wished it.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Finally, on 10 October, officials from the CDU/CSU and the SPD announced that negotiations to form a grand coalition had succeeded.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Angela Merkel would become chancellor and the sixteen seats in the new cabinet (including the Chancellery) would go equally to each side, with the CDU/CSU and the SPD each having eight posts.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Gerhard Schröder would retire from politics.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] Detailed negotiations on the formation of the new government continued into November, with Edmund Stoiber of the CSU withdrawing from the proposed cabinet to continue as Minister-president of Bavaria.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] All three parties held conferences on 14 November which voted to approve the deal.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] The majority of CDU/CSU and SPD delegates in the newly assembled Bundestag elected Merkel as chancellor on 22 November.
[src:angelika-mertens/2005-german-federal-election] 397 members of the Bundestag voted for Merkel, indicating that 51 members from one or more of the SPD, CDU or CSU do not support the coalition deal.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:angelika-mertens/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:angelika-mertens/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Albert Dess graduated from Agricultural college in 1966.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He obtained his Master's in agriculture in 1979.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Albert had a Secondary occupation as farmer and worked in commerce and industry.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He became managing director of a farming cooperative and in 1977, a Full-time farmer/training establishment.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] In 1974 Albert Dess became the District Chairman of the Junge Union.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] In 1981 he became a Member of the CSU district executive and later in 1984, he became the Municipal Chairman of the CSU.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He later rose in ranks by becoming the District Chairman in 1987, Regional Vice-chairman (1989–1995) and Regional Chairman (1995) of the CSU Agricultural Association.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Albert was a Member of the CSU district executive from 1989 and in 1997, a member of the CSU Regional Executive Committee.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] From 1972 to 1996 he was in the Municipal Councillor, Berngau.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He became a District Councillor, Neumarkt/Oberpfalz in 1978.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] In 1984–1996, he was the Vice-chairman of Neumarkt/Oberpfalz district council and from 1984 to 1996, the Mayor of Berngau.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Albert Dess from 1992 to 2004 was the Farm policy spokesman for the CSU Regional Group in the Bundestag and from 1997 to 2004, a Member of the CDU/CSU Group Executive Committee.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He later became the Chairman of the CSU Regional Group working party for Agriculture, Consumer Protection, Environment, Transport, Building and Energy from 2000 to 2004.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Dess was a member of the European Parliament's Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development (AGRI).
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] He was a substitute for the Committee on International Trade (INTRA), a member of the delegation for relations with Mercosur and a substitute for the delegation to the ACP-EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] In May 2018, Dess announced that he would not stand in the 2019 European elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] Outside Germany, Dess is best known for trying to introduce in the European Parliament a Volkswagen-written piece of legislation that would have exempted a whole class of vehicle from pollution controls.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-dess] The proposal was dropped after the Volkswagen emissions violation scandal erupted and Dress has thus far refused requests to comment on his actions.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Probst was born in Garching bei München, Upper Bavaria.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] After graduation in 1951 from the Maximilians Gymnasium in Munich, Probst took an agricultural apprenticeship.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He then studied agricultural sciences at the Technical University of Munich, graduating in 1958 with a diploma as an agricultural engineer.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] In Munich, he served in the Catholic student group K.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He then joined the agricultural civil service, working at the milk research institute at TU Munich.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He left this institute in 1961, after completing research.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He returned to TU Munich in 1963, after two years as an agriculture adviser in France, to work on a research project concerning population genetics.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] At this time he began to participate in municipal politics.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Probst was deputy chair of the culture team of the Christian Socialist Union for many years.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] From 1960 to 1973 he belonged to the country of the circle day of the district of Munich.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He was also a member of the Garching local council from 1966 until 1990.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] From 1969 to 1998 Probst was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He was chair of the Committee on Development and Science from 1972 to 1976, and from 1976 to 1982 chaired the Committee on Research and Technology.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Until 1982, he chaired the science development team and served as spokesperson for the Christian Socialist Union rural group.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Probst was a directly selected delegate of the Munich/Freising constituency in the Bundestag.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] From 1991 to 1999 he represented Germany at parliamentary meetings of the Council of Europe, and at the European Union.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] On 4 October 1982 Probst became Parliamentary Secretary of State at the Federal Ministry for Research and Technology, in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Here he advocated the early provision of computers in schools.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] He served until the Bundestag election in 1990, leaving government on 24 January 1991.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-probst] Probst is married and has four children.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] Rupprecht first became a member of the Bundestag in the 2002 German federal election, representing the Weiden district.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] In parliament, he initially served as deputy chair of the Committee on Economic Affairs from 2005 to 2009.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] In 2009, he moved to the Committee for Education, Research and Technology Assessment.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] Also since 2009, he has been the CDU/CSU parliamentary group's spokesperson on education and research.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] From 2008 to 2010, Rupprecht chaired the parliamentary body providing oversight of the Special Financial Market Stabilization Funds (SoFFin).
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] In the negotiations to form a fourth coalition government under Chancellor Angela Merkel following the 2017 federal elections, Rupprecht was part of the working group on education policy, led by Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, Stefan Müller and Hubertus Heil.
[src:angelika-mertens/albert-rupprecht] In June 2017, Rupprecht voted against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] She was a bookseller and studied economics.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] In 1969 she joined the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and was a member of the Young Socialists.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] Mertens held a municipal council position in Eimsbüttel from 1987 – 1994.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] After successfully running in the 1994 German federal election, Mertens was a member of the *Bundestag*, representing the Hamburg-Eimsbüttel electoral district.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] She was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on transport and building policy from 1998, and then became parliamentary state secretary in the transport ministry during the first and second Schröder cabinet.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] She did not run in the 2005 election, ending her term in the *Bundestag*.
[src:angelika-mertens/angelika-mertens] After leaving parliament, she was chairwoman of the Arbeiter-Samariter-Bund in Hamburg from 2006 until her unexpected death in June 2019.
